{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521880"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13764"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13764"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.13,0.08,0.59,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6384"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115511"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6384"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97514"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7861"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12413"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34908"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42922"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115511"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to a remote Emergency Department, three hours away from the nearest interventional cardiology service, with a 90-minute history of central chest pain. He has no significant medical history and takes sildenafil as required for erectile dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. An ECG shows ST elevation in leads II, III and aVF with reciprocal ST depression in leads I and aVL. As part of the chest pain protocol, the nurse has already administered 300mg aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence oxygen via Hudson mask at 6 L/min","Administer glyceryl trinitrate sublingually","Administer enoxaparin 1 mg/kg subcutaneously","Administer tenecteplase","Commence heparin intravenous infusion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an inferior ST elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) based on the history and ECG findings. In the absence of access to primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) in this remote setting, the most appropriate management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadminister\u003C/strong\u003E thrombolysis with \u003Cstrong\u003Etenecteplase\u003C/strong\u003E in addition to aspirin +/- clopidogrel (depending on cardiology advice from retrieving centre), and arranging urgent retrieval to a PCI-capable hospital.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETenecteplase is indicated in STEMI patients who present within 12 hours of symptom onset when primary PCI cannot be performed within 120 minutes of first medical contact. It is preferred over other thrombolytic agents like alteplase due to ease of administration as a single weight-based bolus. Adjunctive dual antiplatelet therapy with aspirin and clopidogrel reduces the risk of reinfarction. Following thrombolysis, the patient requires urgent retrieval to a PCI-capable hospital for angiography within 24 hours. This allows assessment of the culprit lesion and revascularisation if indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is an important adjunct to thrombolysis in STEMI, but it is administered after the thrombolytic agent. The protocol typically involves an initial intravenous bolus of enoxaparin followed by subcutaneous dosing 15 minutes later. In this scenario, tenecteplase is the priority first step, with enoxaparin following as part of the complete thrombolysis protocol. Unfractionated \u003Cstrong\u003Eheparin\u003C/strong\u003E would only be used instead of enoxaparin in cases of severe renal failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERoutine use of \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxygen\u003C/strong\u003E in normoxic patients with acute coronary syndrome is no longer recommended as it may increase infarct size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlyceryl trinitrate\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in the setting of inferior STEMI with hypotension due to the risk of exacerbating preload reduction. In addition, Glyceryl trinitrate should not be administered in conjunction with sildenafil (PDE-5 inhibitors) due to the risk of profound hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In remote settings without access to primary PCI within 120 minutes of first medical contact, thrombolysis is the reperfusion strategy of choice for STEMI.","Patients with STEMI who receive thrombolysis in remote areas should be retrieved to a PCI-capable hospital for angiography within 24 hours.","Tenecteplase is the preferred thrombolytic agent due to ease of administration (single bolus dose)."],"references":["Nickson DC. STEMI Management. In: Life in the Fast Lane [online]. 2019. Available at: https://litfl.com/stemi-management/","White HD, Van de Werf FJJ. Thrombolysis for acute myocardial infarction. Circulation. 1998;97(16):1632\u201346. Available at: https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/full/10.1161/01.CIR.97.16.1632"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97514"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13764"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97514"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T10:42:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T10:43:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6384"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115511"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"create